    <!-- Report · guide for grown-ups (research-based) -->
    <string name="report_parent_tips_title">Tips for grown-ups</string>
    <string-array name="parent_tips">
        <item>Ask \"how did you solve it?\" instead of \"you\'re so smart\" — kids praised for their method persist longer on hard problems.</item>
        <item>Look at \"problems tried\" and \"problems re-solved\" alongside accuracy — noticing the effort is the best reward.</item>
        <item>Even if math was hard for you, avoid \"I was bad at math too\" in front of a child — math anxiety is contagious.</item>
        <item>On a miss, start with \"how far was it right?\" rather than giving the answer — unpacking the slip together builds skill.</item>
        <item>Ten minutes a day, just check whether the child kept the goal they set — small, near goals build confidence and interest.</item>
    </string-array>

